,"England":"England","Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1360–12 March 1442":"circa 1360–12 maart 1442","1360–1442":"1360–1442","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1380–Female":"1380–Overleden","1314–1419":"1314–1419","1320–1400":"1320–1400","about 1360":"circa 1360","about 1380":"circa 1380","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","about 1419":"circa 1419","1314":"1314","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1442":"1442","1320":"1320","about 1422":"circa 1422","1419":"1419","18 September 1400":"18 september 1400","12 March 1442":"12 maart 1442","Langley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Langley, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Acton Burnell, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1360–12 March 1442":"about 1360–12 March 1442","1360–1442":"1360–1442","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1380–Female":"1380–Deceased","1314–1419":"1314–1419","1320–1400":"1320–1400","about 1360":"about 1360","about 1380":"about 1380","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","about 1419":"about 1419","1314":"1314","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1442":"1442","1320":"1320","about 1422":"about 1422","1419":"1419","18 September 1400":"18 September 1400","12 March 1442":"12 March 1442","Langley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Langley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lee","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sang, Jae, Jong, Jung, Sung, Yong, Kyung, Seung, Dong, Kwang, Myung.","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a meadow or a patch of arable land, Middle English <i>lee</i>, <i>lea</i>, from Old English <i>lēa</i>, dative case (used after a preposition) of <i>lēah</i>, which originally meant ‘wood or glade’.","English: habitational name from any of the many places in England named with Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade’, including Lee in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Kent, and Shropshire, and Lea in Cheshire, Derbyshire, Herefordshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, and Wiltshire."],"variants":[{"name":"Ley","meanings":["English: variant of   Lee  .","German: from a medieval personal name, <i>Eloy</i>, from Latin <i>Eligius</i> (see   Eligio  ), a Christian saint's name.","German (Rhineland): topographic name from Middle High German <i>leie</i> ‘rock, stone, slate’, or a habitational name from any of several places called with this word. Compare   Leier  ."]},{"name":"Lees","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name from Middle English <i>lees</i> ‘fields, arable land’, plural of <i>lee</i> (see   Lee  ), or from Middle English <i>lese</i> ‘pasture, meadow’ (Old English <i>lǣs</i>).","English: habitational name fromLeece or Lees in Lancashire, or Leese in Cheshire, all named from OldEnglish <i>lēas</i> ‘woodland clearings’ (plural of<i>lēah</i>), or from Leece in Cumbria, which was probably namedwith a Celtic word, <i>lïss</i> ‘hall, court, the principalhouse in a district’.","English: variant of   Leece   1."]},{"name":"Lay","meanings":["English: variant of   Lee  .","Scottish: shortened form of   McClay  .","German: habitational name from any of the places so named, in the Rhineland near Koblenz and in Bavaria, from <i>lay(h)</i>, a word meaning ‘stone, rock, slate’."]},{"name":"Laye","meanings":["English: variant of   Lee  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 李, based on its Cantonese pronunciation. See   Li   1."]},{"name":"Lie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Oystein, Sven, Thor.  German Hans, Gunther, Hilde.  Korean Han, Chang Ho, Chen, Chun, Hok, Jung, Kam, Liang, Lie, Ling, Shuen, Yung.","Norwegian: variant of   Li   11, a habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads named Li, from Old Norse <i>hlíth</i> ‘mountain slope, hillside’. In Norway this is the most frequent spelling.","German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Layman","meanings":["English: topographic name for a dweller by a woodland clearing or a meadow, from Middle English <i>ley</i> + <i>man</i>. Compare   Lee  .","English: nickname from <i>layman</i>, a word denoting an uneducated person.","Americanized form of German   Lehmann  ."]},{"name":"Lea","meanings":["English: variant of   Lee  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 李 and 利, see   Li   1 and 3."]},{"name":"Lye","meanings":["English: variant of   Lee   1, a topographic name for someone who lived near a patch of arable land, or a habitational name from Lye in Herefordshire (with the same etymology).","Norwegian: habitational name from a farmstead in Rogaland named Lye, Old Norse <i>Lýgi</i> meaning ‘alliance, covenant’, used to denote a place sanctified by such an agreement, such as a court or council meeting place.","Altered form of German   Ley  ."]},{"name":"Saelee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Chan, Kao, Nai, Chai, Cheng, Chien, Foo, Hin, Muang, Pao, Seng, Song, Sou.","Southeast Asian (Iu Mien): from the name of the Lee clan of the Iu Mien people from Laos + the Thai prefix <i>sae</i>, denoting a clan. Compare   Lee   8."]},{"name":"Leigh","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places (in at least sixteen counties, but especially Leigh in Lancashire) named either with the nominative case of Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’ (see   Lee  ) or with <i>lēage</i>, a late dative form of this word (see   Lye  ).","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 李, based on its Cantonese pronunciation. See   Li   1."]}]},{"name":"Petronella","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Fedele, Francesco, Marco, Salvatore, Vito.","Italian (southern): from <i>Petronella</i>, a feminine pet form of   Petrone   or   Petronio  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Petrone","meanings":["From Latin <i>Petronilla</i>, originally a feminine diminutive of the Roman family name <i>Petronius</i> (of uncertain derivation). The name <i>Petronilla</i> was borne by a 1st-century martyr, and early in the Christian era came to be connected with   Peter  , so that in many legends surrounding her she is described as a companion or even the daughter of  St Peter ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Petronella Lee of Pimhall was born about 1360, in Langley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Roger de la Lee of Pimhall and Langley, was 48 and her mother, Johanna Burnell, was 42. She had at least 1 daughter with Robert Lee de Langley. She died on 12 March 1442, in her hometown, at the age of 83."},"et":{"about 1360–12 March 1442":"umbes 1360–12. märts 1442","1360–1442":"1360–1442","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1314–1419":"1314–1419","1320–1400":"1320–1400","about 1360":"umbes 1360","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","about 1419":"umbes 1419","1314":"1314","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1442":"1442","1320":"1320","about 1422":"umbes 1422","1419":"1419","18 September 1400":"18. september 1400","12 March 1442":"12. märts 1442","Langley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Langley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Acton Burnell, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1360–12 March 1442":"noin 1360–12. maaliskuuta 1442","1360–1442":"1360–1442","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1314–1419":"1314